post_id:
To support our commitment as anti-racist educators and to sustain the work of the school's DEI (Diversity, Equity, & Inclusion) Council, this summer all PHA faculty/staff members received a summer reading book celebrating the work of contemporary Black authors. Book options included memoir, fiction, short-story, and poetry collections, pictured and listed below:

Men We Reaped, by Jesmyn Ward
Fire Shut Up In My Bones, by Charles M. Blow
Survival Math, by Mitchell Jackson
Don't Call Us Dead, by Danez Smith
Counting Descent, by Clint Smith
Citizen: An American Lyric, by Claudia Rankine
Sing, Unburied, Sing, by Jesmyn Ward
Homegoing, by Yaa Gyasi
Friday Black, by Nana Kwame Adjei-Brenyah
Heads of Colored People, by Nafissa Thompson-Spires

shared_text:
The Conscious Kid
August 3 at 10:43 PM ·

We are so excited to share that we partnered up with the YouTube Kids App to create a playlist featuring some of our favorite children’s book read alouds for Reading Month!

We wanted to take this opportunity to center Black authors and stories, which aren’t always included in curriculum or home libraries, but are important for kids of all races to read and have access to from a young age.

Every book we feature is written by a Black author and read aloud by brilliant Black creatives, including @im.angelabassett, @gabunion, @martellusb, @javakasteptoe, @andreapippins, @kwamealexander, and @keturahariel.

Special thanks to YouTube Kids App and the wonderful team we worked with for including us…

post_text: Last week we kicked off our Summer STEAM @ Home programming for K-9 students. PHA participants are taking a variety of enrichment focused classes online led by community partners and our amazing PHA faculty. Classes offered include dance, theater, yoga, earth, computer, and physical science, visual arts, and comic book creation. #JourneyTogether #ExpandedLearning Groundwork Somerville Urbanity Dance MIT Museum KidPowerment Yoga Science From Scientists

May 25 at 4:02 PM ·

link:
Congratulations to the 7 PHA students who received 2020 NCWIT Aspirations in Computing Awards! We are so proud of you!

The award, sponsored by the National Center for Women & Information Technology (NCWIT) recognizes high school students who identify as women, gender queer and non-binary for their computing-related achievements and interests as part of an effort to encourage more young women to choose careers in technology. The students will be honored on Saturday, May 30th during the first-ever award event for all 2020 Award for Aspirations in Computing (AiC) recipients.

Huge congratulations to PHA seniors Syalomee Pradhan, Liam McNally, and Sean Carter on receiving ACE Mentor Program scholarship awards! The students represented 3 out of only 30 high school students in greater Boston who received awards. They were honored in a student showcase event held on March 11.

ACE Mentor Program of Greater Boston is a nonprofit organization which introduces high school students to the architecture, construction, and engineering industries.

If you or someone you know is struggling with food insecurity, Project Bread's FoodSource Hotline offers free, comprehensive statewide food assistance to all Massachusetts residents. Help is offered in 160 languages and there is a line dedicated to helping those that are hearing impaired. For more information and hours, visit www.projectbread.org/gethelp #COVID19

post_text: This morning, students at PHA's High School & Collegiate Institute participated in "Black Expressions," a Black History Month celebration. Renowned hip-hop artists, bloggers, poets, writers, and designers, including our own Director of Technology and graphic novelist Jorge Vega, joined the PHA community to conduct student workshops on their career paths and how being a person of color impacts their work. The workshops were followed by an all-school community meeting where students and faculty had the opportunity to engage with the guest speakers in an illuminating panel discussion.

post_text: We are thrilled to share that Prospect Hill Academy has earned the 2019 College Board AP® Computer Science Female Diversity Award! Schools honored with the award have expanded young women’s access to AP computer science courses. text:
Congratulations to PHA teachers Katie Harris and Ryan Cloke who completed the Chicago Marathon this past Sunday! They ran in memory of former PHA student George Duffaut who passed away from cancer in 2015. In the seven years the two have been involved with the Leukemia & Lymphoma Society's Team in Training under the team name #TheGeorgeEffect, they have raised a combined total of over $35,000 for cancer research and patient treatment.

This was the fourth marathon run for both Harris and Cloke, with Harris finishing with a personal best time of 3:50.12. With Chicago now behind them, they are both looking for their next race, being inspired by a world without cancer and Eliud Kipchoge's "No human is limited."
